    {
      "q": "What is the C-MAPSS dataset?",
      "mode": "openai",
      "answer": "The C-MAPSS (Commercial Modular Aero-Propulsion System Simulation) dataset is a public turbofan engine run-to-failure dataset released by NASA Ames Prognostics Center of Excellence. It contains multivariate time series of engine sensor measurements for fleets of simulated engines operated until functional failure. The dataset is divided into four subsets (FD001-FD004), each varying in operating conditions and fault modes, making it a widely used benchmark for remaining useful life (RUL) prognostics research [cmapss-overview].",
      "citations": [
        "cmapss-overview"
      ],
      "tool_calls": [],
      "seconds": 4.68
    },
    {
      "q": "Why is RUL clipped at 125 cycles in training?",
      "mode": "openai",
      "answer": "The RUL is clipped at 125 cycles during training to focus the model's learning on the degradation regime near failure. Early in an engine's life, there are typically no observable degradation signals, which means that forcing the model to predict large RULs with precision would waste its capacity. By clipping the RUL, the training emphasizes the cycles where meaningful degradation signals emerge, which usually occurs about 30-50 cycles before failure. This approach helps prevent overfitting to noise and allows the model to learn more effectively from the data that reflects actual degradation trends [rul-piecewise], [early-warning].",
      "citations": [
        "rul-piecewise",
        "early-warning"
      ],
      "tool_calls": [],
      "seconds": 4.66
    },
    {
      "q": "Which sensors react most strongly when the HPC degrades?",
      "mode": "openai",
      "answer": "The sensors that react most strongly during High Pressure Compressor (HPC) degradation are T30 (HPC outlet temperature), T50 (LPT outlet temperature), P30 (HPC outlet pressure), Ps30 (HPC outlet pressure), and the turbine coolant bleeds W31/W32. As the HPC wears, these sensors exhibit significant trends: T30 rises as efficiency drops, P30 and Ps30 increase due to the need for more compression work to maintain thrust, T50 rises because of increased combustor load, and W31/W32 rise as the control system attempts to protect downstream hot sections [sensor-trend-hpc], [fault-mode-hpc].",
      "citations": [
        "sensor-trend-hpc",
        "fault-mode-hpc"
      ],
      "tool_calls": [],
      "seconds": 2.86
    },
    {
      "q": "What is the current RUL prediction for engine 17 and what should we do?",
      "mode": "openai",
      "answer": "The current Remaining Useful Life (RUL) prediction for engine 17 is approximately 49 cycles. Given this prediction, the recommended action is to conduct a borescope inspection at the next scheduled stop. This recommendation is appropriate because the predicted RUL falls within the moderate range of 40-80 cycles, indicating that no immediate action is required, but monitoring is essential [rul-definition].\n\nAdditionally, the sensor trends show that while some sensors are stable, others like sensor 3 (T3) are showing a rising trend, which could indicate potential issues that warrant further inspection [rag-why]. Thus, performing the inspection will help gather more evidence and ensure the engine's reliability moving forward.",
      "citations": [
        "rag-why",
        "rul-definition"
      ],
