    {
      "q": "Explain the C-MAPSS asymmetric scoring function and why late predictions are punished harder.",
      "mode": "openai",
      "answer": "The C-MAPSS asymmetric scoring function is designed to evaluate the performance of predictive maintenance models, particularly in the context of Remaining Useful Life (RUL) predictions. It penalizes late predictions more severely than early ones because a late prediction indicates a missed maintenance opportunity, which can lead to catastrophic failures and increased costs. \n\nIn this scoring system, the error \\( d \\) is calculated as the difference between the predicted RUL and the true RUL. If the prediction is early (i.e., \\( d < 0 \\)), the penalty is calculated using the formula \\( \\exp(-d/13) - 1 \\). Conversely, if the prediction is late (i.e., \\( d \\geq 0 \\)), the penalty is given by \\( \\exp(d/10) - 1 \\). This design reflects the critical importance of timely maintenance actions, as failing to predict an engine's failure in advance can result in severe operational and safety consequences [cmapss-scoring]. \n\nThus, the scoring function encourages models to make conservative predictions, ensuring that maintenance is performed before the engine reaches a critical failure point, thereby minimizing risks and costs associated with unexpected failures [cmapss-scoring].",
      "citations": [
        "cmapss-scoring"
